### 1. One-Line Summary

Rakza 7 is the more direct, faster, and more aggressive rubber overall, while Nittaku C-1 is the easier, safer, and more forgiving option with better touch and easier opening play.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Nittaku C-1 feels a bit calmer and easier in soft exchanges, while Rakza 7 gives a slightly stronger rebound and more immediate forward kick.
    * **Top End:** Rakza 7 has the higher ceiling when you swing harder. It carries more finishing speed and feels more decisive on strong drives and power loops.
    * **Linearity:** Nittaku C-1 is generally more predictable and easier to regulate shot by shot. Rakza 7 is still quite controllable, but it has more built-in punch and a more noticeable catapult.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Nittaku C-1 is easier for lifting backspin because the softer feel and longer ball hold make the first topspin feel more automatic. Rakza 7 can also open well, but it rewards a slightly cleaner, more committed contact.
    * **Max Spin:** Rakza 7 has the stronger upper-end spin when you engage the sponge fully. Nittaku C-1 produces very good spin, but it is more about easy access than outright maximum rotation.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both are grippy non-tacky rubbers. Rakza 7 feels a little more aggressive and bitey on full contact, while Nittaku C-1 feels a bit softer and more forgiving.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Nittaku C-1 tends to give the easier, slightly safer arc on opening loops and controlled topspin exchanges. Rakza 7 usually comes out a bit more direct and penetrating.
    * **Safety:** Nittaku C-1 gives more natural net clearance in many rally situations. Rakza 7 is very safe once you are dialed in, but it feels less automatic than C-1 on softer or less committed attacks.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza 7 feels firmer, denser, and more solid at impact. Nittaku C-1 feels softer, more elastic, and easier on the hand, especially on backhand-oriented strokes.
    * **Dwell:** Nittaku C-1 holds the ball a bit longer, which helps with spin creation and touch. Rakza 7 has enough dwell for quality topspin, but the contact is more compact and direct.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Nittaku C-1 is the less sensitive rubber overall and is easier to manage against incoming spin. Rakza 7 is not difficult, but it reacts a little more actively.
    * **Touch Play:** Nittaku C-1 is better for short pushes, controlled receives, and delicate placement. Rakza 7 can still play short well, but it asks for slightly finer touch because of its stronger rebound.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Nittaku C-1 is easier and more forgiving on passive blocks. It absorbs pace better and keeps the ball on the table with less effort.
    * **Active Counter:** Rakza 7 is stronger when you punch, counterdrive, or re-accelerate the ball. It feels more dangerous and more stable when you actively take initiative.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * you want the more offensive rubber with better finishing speed and stronger direct pressure.
    * you like a firmer, more solid contact and do not mind a bit more rebound.
    * you play an assertive topspin game and want a rubber that still works well on both forehand and stronger backhand attacks.

* **Choose Nittaku C-1 if:**
    * you want the easier rubber for control, touch, opening loops, and backhand stability.
    * you prefer a softer feel with more dwell and a more forgiving response.
    * you value consistency, short game comfort, and simple access to spin more than maximum speed.
